# English → Persian Translation Benchmark using LLMs (MBART, FLAN-T5, Gemma)
# Project Overview
This project explores and compares different Large Language Models (LLMs) for English → Persian translation, using both:
•	Pretrained multilingual seq2seq models (MBART)
•	Instruction-based models (FLAN-T5)
•	Large instruction-tuned LLMs (Gemma)
•	Prompt engineering and in-context learning (few-shot prompting)
•	Evaluation using BLEU score (SacreBLEU)
The main goal is to analyze how model architecture and prompting strategies affect translation quality, especially for low-resource languages like Persian.
________________________________________
🎯 Objectives
•	Evaluate baseline translation performance of MBART without prompting
•	Improve translation using few-shot in-context learning (ICL)
•	Analyze issues in instruction-following for seq2seq models
•	Compare LLM-based translation with Google Translate baseline
•	Experiment with larger instruction-tuned models (Gemma)
•	Evaluate all systems using BLEU score
________________________________________
🧠 Models Used
1. MBART (facebook/mbart-large-50-many-to-many-mmt)
•	Multilingual seq2seq model
•	Supports Persian (fa_IR)
•	Used for baseline translation and few-shot prompting
2. FLAN-T5 (google/flan-t5-base)
•	Instruction-tuned model
•	Tested for zero-shot summarization and multilingual limitations
3. Gemma (google/gemma-2-9b-it)
•	Large instruction-tuned LLM
•	Used for improved translation with few-shot prompting
________________________________________
📊 Dataset
A custom parallel dataset of:
•	10 English sentences
•	10 Persian reference translations
Used for:
•	Translation benchmarking
•	BLEU score evaluation
•	Prompt engineering experiments
________________________________________
⚙️ Methodology
🔹 1. Baseline Translation (MBART)
•	Direct translation without prompting
•	Measures raw capability of pretrained model
•	Shows limitations in instruction-following behavior
________________________________________
🔹 2. Few-Shot In-Context Learning (ICL)
•	Added example sentence pairs in prompt
•	Structured prompt format:
English: ...
Persian: ...

English: ...
Persian: ...
•	Improved contextual understanding
________________________________________
🔹 3. Output Post-Processing
MBART often:
•	Repeats prompts
•	Generates structured text instead of only translation
To fix this:
•	Custom cleaning function extracts only final Persian output
________________________________________
🔹 4. Evaluation Metric
•	BLEU score (using sacrebleu)
•	Comparison with Google Translate baseline
________________________________________
🔹 5. Gemma Experiments
•	Used instruction-tuned LLM (Gemma 2B / 9B)
•	Applied few-shot prompting
•	Controlled decoding:
o	temperature
o	repetition penalty
o	beam search
________________________________________
📈 Results Summary
Model	Approach	Performance
MBART	Zero-shot	Baseline (~28 BLEU)
MBART + ICL	Few-shot prompting	Improved consistency
Gemma	Instruction + ICL	More fluent translations
Google Translate	External baseline	Strong reference system
________________________________________
🔍 Key Findings
•	MBART is strong for translation but not instruction-following
•	Few-shot prompting improves structure but may cause repetition
•	Post-processing is necessary for clean evaluation
•	Larger instruction-tuned models (Gemma) produce:
o	More fluent outputs
o	Better prompt adherence
•	BLEU score alone does not capture all quality aspects
________________________________________
⚠️ Challenges
•	Prompt repetition in MBART outputs
•	Tokenization differences across models
•	Handling Persian language formatting
•	Context window limitations (512 tokens in MBART)
•	Ensuring fair BLEU evaluation after post-processing
________________________________________
🧰 Tech Stack
•	Python
•	Hugging Face Transformers
•	PyTorch
•	SacreBLEU
•	Google Translate API
•	MBART / FLAN-T5 / Gemma

________________________________________
⭐ Conclusion
This project demonstrates how:
•	Prompt engineering
•	Model choice
•	Few-shot learning
•	Post-processing
can significantly impact LLM performance in multilingual tasks.
It highlights the gap between:
•	pretrained seq2seq models (MBART)
•	instruction-tuned LLMs (Gemma)
and shows how modern LLM techniques improve translation quality for low-resource languages like Persian.

